Back when War Room first came out, I had mixed feelings about the premise. This sounds like another cheesy romance drama in which the couple learns the power of faith to overcome any trial in an unbelievably short amount of time.
In many ways, this is another cheesy romance drama because thats exactly what happens. Its the elements added to the mix of drama that makes this movie worth watching.

Following are five reasons to watch War Room with the family.

Family Friendly
As more of my close friends get married, I begin to think more about what I would be okay watching with a younger audience. Unlike many secular romance films, the focus of War Room is not on the romantic drama or the specific individuals involved. Its clear that there is a higher power at work here.

The film also doesnt contain inappropriate content for children. (See the content rating below for more details.)

Miss Clara
Whenever Miss Clara appeared on the screen, my family and I knew we were in for some laughs. She is a little woman with a fierce spirit and strong faith. I love her faith for the Lord. Her war room and tips on starting a prayer life inspired me to start a prayer journal.

I can easily see Miss Clara becoming a family favorite. Shes certainly my favorite character!

Character Development
Though War Room initially portrays a dysfunctional family, its clear from the beginning that this isn't a good situation and that something needs to change (and will change). Both Elizabeth and Tony have their own issues to work out individually before their relationship can change; its powerful to see the transformation that faith works in their lives and subsequently their relationship. The scenes with their daughter at the end are especially heartwarming.

Good Morals
War Room portrays good morals that I would want to instill in a younger audience. Some of these values include the importance of respecting your partner, being there for your family, having a good work ethic, and meeting with a mentor figure for guidance.

Demonstrates the Power of Prayer
Lastly, War Room demonstrates the power of prayer. While some of the scenes may seem out there (such as the one where Miss Clara commands the thief to lay down his weapon in Jesuss name), one consistent theme in the movie is the significance of having a strong prayer life.

Along with this theme comes the truth that we cannot do anything on our own. We cannot create a change in someone elses life on our own. In the end, our peace comes from God, and our requests need to be made known to God. I saw somewhere that the times we think we don't have enough time to pray are the times we most need to pray, and this idea is supported in War Room.

FINAL THOUGHTS
War Room is an inspiring, heartwarming film that that will encourage believers to strengthen their prayer life and to reconsider their relationships with loved ones in light of Scripture. This is a film that I want to share with loved ones because of all the reasons listed above and because I don't want them to miss out on the message of the power of prayer and faith to work a radical transformation in our lives.

I had heard about War Room and purchased it on the cheap. I know my wife wanted to view it, and I agreed to do so with her.

I didn't hate the movie. But I didn't like it either. The scripting was formulaic, the plot line was predictable and the dialogue became quite preachy at times. I found the characterizations to be trite, if not cliched. Pacing was not conducive to keeping gainful attention - it became rather boring at times. And the movie didn't seem to know how to end. Several times I assumed the ending had arrived, but it just kept going.

I still don't know the point of including the rope jumping tournament towards the end as the premise of the film was not at all like Karate Kid. Yet it seemed to want to stray in that direction. It was not a segment that added anything to the plot overall.

The movie lacked nuance. It lacked any kind of surprise at any point along its timeline. And it really lacked strong performances, though I wouldn't call them bad. Mediocre maybe. Vanilla definitely.

The Kendricks have a well-defined market for their work. And there's nothing wrong with the idea of Christian art in any of its manifestations. But goodness, it has to be compelling. It has to be able to reach across the aisle, so to speak. If it can't, then all it's doing is preaching to a noncritical choir.  Where is the ministry in that?

I heard so much about this movie that I had to order it.  I hoped to be inspired and come away with strong, lasting feelings that would encourage me to spend more time in prayer.  Unfortunately, it was just an "okay" movie that didn't have quite the impact I expected.  I doubt I will watch it a second time.  The story idea was a good one, but a bit unrealistic in that problems were often solved more quickly than in actual life.  Example is when the man was dining with another woman and got sick as his wife was at home praying.  God usually takes awhile to work everything out and often appears to arrive too late in the real world.  The movie did motivate me to start a prayer journal to keep a record of prayers offered and answers to prayer.  As far as going into an actual closet to pray, most people don't have one, but I did designate a guest room as my "war room."  This movie is good, family entertainment as it is a positive one that emphasizes Christian values.  I was just looking to be more moved with feelings that touched my heart more deeply, something like those I felt after watching "Fiddler on the Roof."  Unfortunately, this movie didn't do it for me.  I still think it's worthwhile to watch, however, as it does emphasize the power of prayer and reminds people that God hears & answers us when we call out to Him.

Every so often, I browse the Christian inspiration books to see what's new because there are so many great books to read! During one of my searches, I saw this movie as a suggestion and I was curious to see what it was about. I love Christian movies so I ended up borrowing it from my local library. Well, I loved it so much I ordered my own copy right away so I can watch it again and again! War Room is a movie that stars Priscilla Shirer (author of a number of books including Awaken: 90 Days with the God who Speaks). Elizabeth (Shirer) and her husband Tony have what appears to be a wonderful life to anyone who looks at them. They both have great jobs, a large, beautiful house, and an adorable daughter. Behind closed doors, they snap at each other and hardly spend any quality time together. Elizabeth is a real estate agent and meets with an elderly woman, Miss Clara, to help sell her house. Miss Clara is very spiritual and can sense that a lot is wrong in Elizabeth's life. She persuades Elizabeth to meet her at her house and she shows her her "war room" and the power of prayer. What starts out as solely a job will end up transforming the lives for everyone involved. I've watched some movies that I have no interest in seeing again but this is one I want to watch many times which is why I bought my own copy! I loved it so much and cried through most of it, some happy tears and some sad tears. It's so powerful and touched me immensely. I even learned from it. I very highly recommend this movie if you enjoy Christian dramas and I am interested in other movies directed by Alex Kendrick plus I now have a stack of Priscilla Shirer books to read!

It is well known and loved, a favorite among believers!

I admit to not being a churchy person.  However, I have great respect for people holding to their Christian values these days. I have been looking for movies that are enriching, rather than the negative  trash that Hollywood produces.  I have  watched only a few  "Christian" films  and  was not impressed, However, I decided to give them them another try.  Some of the earlier ones were awful, production-wise, syrupy, and the message somehow seemed remote from real life.  Christian film makers have certainly upped their game.  War Room was very well made. The story deals with  very universal problems and challenges encountered in family, marriage, faith, and how to live in an increasingly secular world with all its enticements. I am very critical and picky about message films of any any ilk, however this one was a winner.  I thought it had an honesty, clarity and reality to it that earlier Christian films didn't.  Great family viewing with some good talking points to discuss as a family.  We live in an age that is increasingly replacing prayer with such new age alternatives as meditation and mindfulness.  I may not attend church, but I know from experience  that nothing replaces prayer.

Viewers of War Room will understand the aptness of comparing a military war-planning session to earnest private prayer - and will find their faith strengthened.  This excellently produced drama delivers a serious coaching session on "living out what you really believe."  You'll laugh and cry at the same time.  The screenplay is tightly constructed to hold interest and build suspense, and breathes sincerity and zeal.  Its underlying doctrine (for every screenplay, every movie, indeed projects a point-of-view) is orthodox Christianity, plain and simple.  The quality of acting and presentation is skillfully good, and enhanced the film's message.  We saw the movie on a military base, where the audiences (in multiple showings) enthusiastically cheered the film's happy ending, and thoughtfully recommended the movie to others on base.  We think this movie is worth buying and showing to guests in our home; it's been heart-warming to see it again and know the effect of the "call to prayer" is cumulative.

In "War Room" (2015), a Christian film from the Kendrick brothers, real estate agent Elizabeth and her husband Tony are struggling in their marriage.  But with the help of her elderly client Clara, Elizabeth learns to use a new weapon in her battles: prayer.  Can she show grace to her husband while depending on God, and how will her husband deal with the temptations of selfishness, materialism, and infidelity?

Christians don't typically have a strong track record in producing films or fiction that is of high quality both artistically and theologically, so I was impressed with the overall quality of this film on both a cinematic and a thematic level.  There's some pretty good acting (most characters are African-American), and punctuating the script at regular intervals are insightful one-liners filled with Biblical wisdom.  There's also a good mix of warm humour (e.g. the recurring joke with Liz' smelly shoes, which gets a great pay-off at the end), and particularly in the character of Clara.

The main themes of the film relate to prayer and marriage.  Elizabeth comes to exemplify the Biblical picture of a godly wife in a difficult situation just as 1 Peter 3 commends, as she learns that her real battle isn't against her husband, but against sin and Satan.  She humbly discovers that this is the real fight, which needs to be fought with dependence on God.  As such, she has to love her husband despite his wrongs, even though he doesn't deserve grace, in the awareness that she herself doesn't deserve grace from God.  The film is generally filled with good spiritual advice, especially about marriage, and does a good job of showing the ugliness of marital infidelity and the beauty of marital faithfulness, in a welcome contrast to most of what is offered by Hollywood; it also shows something of the foolishness and destructiveness of materialism.  Some critics have blasted the film for what they see as endorsing abusive relationships and encouraging submission and prayer as the answer to spousal abuse, but personally I thought that the movie's approach was quite Biblical in that regard.

For the most part the theme of prayer is handled respectfully, with the use of the Bible for prayer content especially being a positive highlight.  I initially thought that the idea of a "prayer room" would prove to be cheesy, but the film mostly handled this concept of Clara's "war room" tactfully, with just the right blend of the light-hearted and the serious (an unfortunate exception being at the end when a retired pastor supposedly senses in a mystical way that the room was used for prayer).

I also appreciated the fact that the film doesn't end as soon as one of the characters has a `conversion' experience; it also avoids the temptation to provide a "feel good" moment towards the end in which the main characters might have won first place in a sporting event.  Importantly, it goes on to show what active faith looks like in the ongoing battles of life that need to be fought by Christians.  This makes "War Room" an improvement over the plot of "Fireproof", which more or less concludes as soon as both characters come to faith.  Here the movie continues for another 40 minutes just when you think it is done,  going on to deal well with the need to address the consequences of sin, including the concept of restitution.

That's not to say the film is beyond all criticism.  Clara's method of telling an assailant to put down a knife in the name of Jesus isn't one to be imitated in the real world.  Elizabeth's monologue in which she tells the devil to get out in Jesus' name and to go back to hell is not only over the top, but a conversation with Satan is not what the Bible means when it says we are to resist the devil; so these aspects are theologically unsound.  The fact that some of those involved in the film (Priscilla Shirer and Beth Moore) are advocates of the new age practice of "contemplative prayer" is also troubling, as is the fact that the marketing machine around the film is closely connected to doctrines in other areas that could be dangerous (e.g. the heavenly tourism movement). At one point I wondered if Clara was making a false dilemma in saying that it wasn't Elizabeth's job to fix her husband but just to love and respect him.  While this is mostly true, at the same time we have a responsibility to both pray and work, which Clara herself later acknowledges.  I also couldn't help but wonder if the film's somewhat glib ending could be discouraging or give false hope to those who don't experience happy endings in real life.  At one point Elizabeth says "I'm eating dessert while my husband is rubbing my feet - there has got to be a God in heaven" - but what about all the godly women who must soldier on with unrepentant husbands?  God is not a magic genie who will always make everything turn out okay in the end.  Although it wouldn't be fair to expect an entire theology about prayer in a film like this, the movie could also convey the unintended implication that prayer is mostly about asking God for things rather than thanking and praising Him.

There are other blemishes beyond the above-mentioned ones related to prayer, such as the emphasis on Jesus without mention of the Father or the Spirit, and one instance of veiled blasphemy ("gosh").  The film also seems to normalize working mothers/wives, although thankfully there is a hint from Elizabeth that perhaps she and her husband had made a bad decision in being so career oriented early on in their marriage.  Elizabeth's need to forgive her husband shouldn't be completely disconnected from his repentance, and the film isn't as clear on this point as it could be.

But these criticisms aside, overall I found the film to have a refreshingly positive and Biblical message.  Although there were minor theological weaknesses, the main message about prayer and marriage is sound: the real struggle in marriage is the battle against sin, not your spouse, and to fight that battle you need God's help in showing grace just as you've experienced grace.  This message is sound and comes across clearly, and thankfully this positive theme isn't accompanied with the embarrassingly low production qualities that sometimes afflict attempts at Christian cinema.  As such, "War Room" is a welcome alternative to the toxic messages that typically saturate Hollywood movies, and can be recommended for discerning and mature Christian viewers. - GODLY GADFLY

This is a Christian movie that talks about Jesus, God and your involvement in church. I know a lot of viewers have their complaints about the movie, but it's the message that counts. This movie is about spiritual warfare, and how the enemy operates on various levels. It's a film about fervently praying and how prayer can change your life, your marriage, and family issues. In this film, Elizabeth Jordan, played by Priscilla Shirer, is learning how to pray and let God lead. She is learning that her battles within her family and her marriage are not physical, but rather spiritual, and now must develop a strategy in order to fight the enemy through prayer. She is being taught by Miss Clara, an elderly woman who prayed to God to send her someone whom she could teach what she had learned through prayer. If you do not believe in the power of prayer and how being consistent in prayer can change your life, then this movie is not for you. It has deep religious overtones, and therefore, may appear as mythology to the non-believer. But for those who believe in the power of prayer, it is a must add to your video library.

This movie continues to inspire me to pray and leave to God the things that only He is able to accomplish. And that a relationship with God is what we should be seeking above all else, including trusting God to fight our battles for us. I would caution those who are going through very hard times a couple things - not every difficult situation turns out perfectly fine in the end as this movie portrays, and may seem to promise. Some people pray for their marriages and a wayward spouse still leaves. Or does not stop abusing. Or any one of a number of temporal bad outcomes that may take years to resolve in this lifetime. Some situations never do resolve in this lifetime, and God is still faithful to His children. The second caution I would have is to warn people, just because you pray a lot does not mean you can will an armed robber to put down his weapon in the name of Jesus, and expect the robber to comply with you. Don't put God to the test like that. He is not a cosmic vending machine. Because I am aware of these things, I still give the movie 5 stars on account of its overall message to seek the Lord, to turn from sin, and to pray and pour out our hearts to Him.

I can't give this movie just 1 star (even though I utterly disagree with the spirituality promoted) because I loved watching the character of the young daughter, and I LOVED the scenes, near the end, of the Double Dutch jump rope competition.  We need more upbeat and fun community activities like Double Dutch jump roping, and I am glad I watched the film just to have seen that part.

Yet the movie actively and intentionally promotes a certain belief system about God and prayer, and if I judged it solely from that perspective the film would get 1 star.  Because this is what I see depicted in the film: the machinations of the Deceiver in a film produced by people who are deceived. I know that sounds harsh, but as the Bible says in Amos 8:10 (New Living Translation), "How you hate those who tell the truth!"  And Jude 1:10:  "Men revile the things which they do not understand."  I.e., truth is hate to those who hate the truth.

My understanding of prayer is that it is a very personal act focused on the relationship between the person praying and God. I.e., the type of prayer to which God responds asks God to help THE PERSON WHO IS PRAYING change his/her attitudes, actions, beliefs, character, etc. in order to further God's Kingdom on earth. So this film rubbed me the wrong way when it depicted the main character praying to God to "interrupt her husband's sin," then cutting to the husband and depicting him suddenly being stricken ill (i.e., God's immediate positive response to the main character's prayer). It is my understanding and experience that only the Deceiver responds to "prayer" in this fashion, not God.

God created us each with an ego and free will, meaning that each of us has sovereignty over our own minds and bodies until we give that sovereignty away. Ideally we should realize early in life that we can only live our best lives if God is sovereign, and, thus, freely choose to return to Him the sovereignty He gave us at birth. There are many factors which preclude children from doing this, however: some are born inherently prideful and stubborn, more are not given the nurturing they need in order to trust that God (Creation, Life, the Universe) genuinely loves them and can be trusted with their lives, and MANY are indoctrinated into religious beliefs which distort their perceptions of God and what He wants from us (including what type of prayer He desires).

As a result, most people do not have their characters formed "into the image of God" as they grow and develop, and they do not really try to give themselves to God until they feel broken and unequal to the challenges of life. So instead of offering themselves to God as whole human beings, aware of their own worth as individual human beings (which I believe is a prerequisite to inviting the true Creator into one's life!) they turn to "god" in a panic or out of a sense of worthlessness, with the desire for "a power larger than themselves" to rush in to "save the day." What they do not realize is that they likely gave sovereignty away long, long before (they might even be psychologically damaged and not know it) and anyone who desires supernatural assistance only when they are damaged and weak is literally inviting deception. In an ignorant state of weakness and need, they invite the Deceiver to rush in and pretend to be God (or Jesus Christ).

But don't misunderstand me: God has compassion for those who are broken and weak, and it is not a state of brokenness alone which invites deception. It is a state of brokenness in a person who still, nevertheless, does not have the desire to put God's agenda first. What he/she wants, instead, is supernatural assistance in fulfilling a worldly agenda created by him/herself, or by the larger society: an agenda of prosperity, good marriage, decent employment, healthy children, etc. It's not that the real God doesn't want these same things for those who serve Him -- He does -- but He provides them in His way and in His time (the way HE defines them, not the way the world defines them) as a natural consequence of living life as it was designed to be lived, to those who genuinely desire nothing other than to do what God would have them do (with no stipulations or expectations).

This means that you would cling to Him and do His will even if He allowed the world to strip every positive thing from your life -- like what happened to Job -- with no indication or promise that any of it would ever be returned to you.

If most "believers in Jesus Christ as Lord and Savior" really examined their motives and beliefs, and had the capacity to be brutally honest with themselves (which most deceived people do not, by the way), they would realize that what they sought when they "invited Jesus Christ into my heart as Lord and Savior" was the presence of a supernatural power which promised to fulfill personal desires. The only supernatural power which responds to calls of this kind is the Deceiver, who pretends to be God or Jesus, and has a vast arsenal of tricks to wow the human mind and psyche into believing -- for a period of time -- that he or she is now "in the hands of" the real thing.

To return to the scene where God pricks the conscience of the about-to-cheat husband (and/or makes the husband physically ill in order to prevent him from cheating): God does not pre-empt the free will and decision of an individual at the request of another individual, no matter how righteous the request may appear, because He has chosen to exercise dominion only over the lives of individuals who first make a personal decision that they need His direction. Period.

In this film, the "War Room" refers to a room where the characters prayed together to call on God for help, protection and comfort. Now, as a practicing Christian, I enjoyed the film. It was well-made and the actors played their roles, well. However, for those who are not Christians, it could seem very "tedious and preachy," which is how the film was described to me by my husband. My husband and parents all disliked the film, because it was too heavy and seemed like they were being preached at. I realise the scriptwriter and book's author meant well, but I don't think it is a very good evangelical tool, because it puts people off, who are not strong Christians. For a non-believer or a "not sure" agnostic, "Left Behind" the film and book by Tim LaHaye would probably be more on the mark. (Note: the "Left Behind" book series is far superior to the film version. I haven't seen the re-make with Nicholas Cage, yet, so it may be better.)

Full disclosure: I am a devout Christian and I have no interest in mocking anyone's religious beliefs.

There is an old fable about a man who's stuck in a flood, so he prays to God. A raft floats by and they offer to let him aboard. "No," he says, "God will save me." The flood waters rise higher, and a boat comes by and offers him a place, only to earn the same response. Finally, the flood waters are so high that the man is stuck on his roof. He continues to pray fervently. A helicopter offers to let down a ladder so he can climb to safety. "No," he shouts up at them. "I'm sure that God will save me any time now!" Finally, the floodwaters overtake the house and the man is drowned. When he arrives in heaven, he asks, "God, why didn't you save me from the flood?" God replies, "I sent you a raft, a boat, and a helicopter! What more could you want?"

This movie is what happens when that man tries to make a film about marital problems.

Rather than calmly and maturely confronting her wayward husband, seeking out marital therapy (whether through a pastor or a licensed therapist), or even going so far as to seek out a trial separation or even divorce (which, unfortunately, the husband's abusive, manipulative, criminal, and cheating behaviour truly does merit), the wife chooses to pray...which is all well and good, but she also chooses to do nothing else. Though it works (kind of) in this movie, it is unfortunately a dangerous message for people caught in an unhealthy marriage. God does indeed answer our prayers more often than not, but pushing the message that He'll cater to us while we sit on our behinds and refuse to put in a bit of manual labor of our own is neither realistic nor helpful.
This movie had me in tears through a few scenes. What a fantastic movie and evidence that God is real, we just need to move out of the way sometimes and let him handle things.

This is one of THE WORST MOVIES EVER MADE.

First of all, let's start wit the fact that this is basically Tyler Perry's Fireproof--an absolute blackface beat-for-beat remake of Cameron's awful film. It gets WAY more dangerous than that though. This film encourages people to turn to blind faith for everything from failing, abusive marriages to knifepoint muggings.  The characters are very thin caricatures portrayed by evangelical motivational speakers, not actors and it SHOWS. Instead of having one or two key problems to resolve, these characters have an absolute laundry list of serious issues all happening at once. It takes a lot away from the film, which is actually surprising, iven how bad it is in general.

Let me tell you something. COMMUNICATION BEING RESTORED is what incidentally "saved" these characters' marriage, not the "hand of God". I don't know if that was accidental or purposeful, but it does kind of screw up the narrative.  Oh, and the way God "forgives" the husband character for his felony drug dealing? Yeah. THAT'S not farfetched or dangerous at all.

It also ends with getting INSANELY preachy; prosceletizing about how everything needs more Jesus--schools, Congress, law enforcement, etc. If they all only submitted to Christian mythology EVERYTHING would magically get all better. As naive and self-serving as this is, the way it's tacked on at the end of the whole family story is lazy at best.

I still just can't get over the horrendous "message" this film bungles out. Don't seek marriage counseling. Just go in a closet and complain to the Lord. Are you stealing from the company you work for and dealing drugs on the side while starting an affair while verbally abusing your wife? The magic of JESUS can fix it all!

I'm not sure non-devoted Christians would "get" this film.  I love that the Kendrick brothers make films specifically for a specific audience (faithful evangelical Christians and Catholics) and don't try to be everything to everyone.

As a filmmaker, it's amazing how he has able to get such competent performances out of non-professional actors.  The story is crisp, the dialog is very good and the production values even are worthy of a middle budget Hollywood film.

As a Christian however, it is a great effort that does a wonderful job of demonstrating how prayer and faith can do the impossible.  I take exception with a bit of the doctrine that tries to exalt religious performance (ie, doing good) over trust in Jesus to guide a Christian and affect change, but overall it is a movie that WILL inspire Christians to pray.  And that is a very good thing.

First:  Here's the only (minor) flaw in the movie:
There are tiny moments when the script feels stilted, primarily because the actors usually speak clearly and separately, without much talking over each other, interrupting, natural fumbling, etc.  (Script writers: for next time, watch carefully the masterful background dialogue in "It's a Wonderful Life")  The producers clearly wanted the message to come across plainly, which they accomplish beautifully.  However, the movie is still a joy to watch.  The male lead is a superb actor, and the female lead beautiful and likable, the daughter darling. My kids (ages 7-14) all sat through it multiple times and loved it. What's more, they all could clearly understand the details, without my supplementing with a lot of explanation.

But this movie is for every adult, no matter how wonderful and happy your own marriage.  We're all touched by the themes of conflict and honesty.  This movie has plenty of real conflict that will resonate with every viewer as well as a yearning for God's involvement in our families.  I'm a Mormon, and I wholeheartedly wish this film would go far beyond the traditional evangelical audience to people of all faiths.  It is powerfully relevant to us all!  I have recommended this movie to everyone I know because it is so deeply moving.

The best part of the movie is that it doesn't just show a repentant father, complete with masterful confessions. It shows the JOY afterward.  This movie shows the FRUITS of righteous living.  So many movies end with the change of heart, but they don't let you rejoice in the happy times that come later.  Or they end when the couple come together, but don't let you enjoy the following romance for more than 2-3 final moments.  This one is different.  There's so much happiness at the end that you feel the glory of God in it.

There's a reason this movie is phenomenal. Simply put, it's inspired by God. He has used the Kendrick brothers powerfully. I don't know much about them at this point except to say I have seen Courageous and Fireproof (both touching movies in their own right). Their latest masterpiece, and it is just that: a masterpiece that is an emotionally driven, thought provoking adventure, wonderfully made perfect for the human race.

I wonder about the motivation for casting African-American actors in the major roles. Is it due to the strife we all have been exposed to lately? Yet it works. The three main characters - Tony, Elizabeth and Clara are worthy of Oscar award winning performances. The film goes much deeper. The focus is on prayer. Throughout the Bible there are numerous accounts of God's chosen people repenting of their sins followed by His blessing them bountifully. I wonder why mankind can not learn from its sordid past, and instead embrace its times of triumph so we can, once and for all, truly love one another?

We live in troubling times, this movie on an individual level demonstrates that each one of us can make a difference in our own little corner of the world... and it all begins with prayer and a love of God as Elizabeth so aptly points out emerging from her prayer closet while Clara continues to march to the beat of the Almighty drummer.

Tony has the courage of his convictions to turn from his wicked ways and embrace the Lord. While many in life have difficulty embracing this, indeed all of us go through it; his leap of faith supported by his loving wife demonstrates that we need to let go and let God work a miracle in our lives. Often we make proverbial mountains of fear out of what typically tend to be irritating molehills. On the other hand, we may just be too complacent to care about each other deeply. Perhaps we need to embrace John 3:16 a little more.

Some may argue that the movie ends happily for all and that's just not the way it is in real life. However for all the distress that occurs these days, how much of it due to the "lack of prayer"? The movie ends with a screen shot of 2 Chronicles 7:14, "if my people, who are called by my name, will humble themselves and pray and seek my face and turn from their wicked ways, then I will hear from heaven and will forgive their sin and will heal their land."

Prayer moves mountains and saves lives. Literally. That is the precept of this movie. It encourages everyone to come together in prayer for their families, their friends, their co-workers, their communities and their nation. Just imagine how life in these United States and for that matter, the world would be if we became a praying nation and a praying planet for the Almighty Creator of the Universe!

On a related note, it was humorous, humble and lighthearted to see how the story line of Liz's not so sweet-smelling feet played through the film. Could this be a modern day "thorn in the flesh"? Or a chance at redeeming some humility made popular by the greatest man who ever lived and walked on this earth 2000 years ago.

It was delightful to see the jump rope competitions to see such energetic and talented young people participate in a wholesome, family friendly activity that proved to be extremely entertaining.

The original soundtrack was superb from the movie's theatrical score to the songs by various contemporary Christian artists. The camerawork was perfect. The sound excellent, if there was one drawback and a small one at that - it would be the lighting of some of the scenes that seemed they could use a little more intensity at times, yet that pales in comparison to the overall work of art this visual masterpiece has and will become.

This presentation gives  very realistic  family situations within our current culture showing the spiritual battle we face against Satan's attacks.  The War Room prayer closet illustrates God's instruction and promises for victory over Satan's attacks so powerfully portrayed through the life of the elderly home owner's witness to her real estate agent whose marriage is falling apart.  When the agent begins to practice a daily prayer time in her own prayer closet and begins to claim God's promises, she begins to see a change in her own outlook and within her husband's behavior. A  true to life story powerfully and skillfully illustrated in this DVD.  I purchased a copy and took it with me to leave with our church family in the Philippines.

From the award-winning creators of Fireproof and Courageous comes War Room, a compelling drama with humor and heart that explores the power that prayer can have on marriages, parenting, careers, friendships, and every other area of our lives. Tony and Elizabeth Jordan have it all  great jobs, a beautiful daughter, and their dream house. But appearances can be deceiving. Tony and Elizabeth Jordans world is actually crumbling under the strain of a failing marriage. While Tony basks in his professional success and flirts with temptation, Elizabeth resigns herself to increasing bitterness. But their lives take an unexpected turn when Elizabeth meets her newest client, Miss Clara, and is challenged to establish a war room and a battle plan of prayer for her family. As Elizabeth tries to fight for her family, Tonys hidden struggles come to light. Tony must decide if he will make amends to his family and prove Miss Claras wisdom that victories don't come by accident.

It was a good movie, but they are often praying to Jesus, instead of the holy Father. I believe in the Godhead which includes: God the Father, God the Son (Jesus Christ), and God the Holy Spirit, but after doing an intensive study, I don't believe you should pray to anyone but God the Father.  So, I couldn't get past this, what I call an error, that permeates the christian world today, and therefore, only 2 stars.  Doing what is right, what we have been instructed to do, will bring often bring good results.  But, it doesn't always work out the way we want it to.  Sometimes, when God doesn't answer our prayers the way we want, then we find a better blessing.  Sometimes, we never get a blessing, because we need to be guided in a more perfect way. Remember when Jesus died, he was alone, except for his mother and other women, and Apostle John. All the Apostles, (except John) and many, many Christians were persecuted, were murdered, dying horrible deaths. We must remain faithful, even to the end. We must use prayer to ask God the Father for our needs - can even argue with Him, and praise Him, but we must pray, as Jesus did, "Not my will, but thine (yours - God the Father), because our Creator knows what's best for us. Or, if we have the right attitude, regardless of how our prayers are answered, we are an inspiration to others to be followers of Jesus Christ, who are allowed the opportunity to be right with God the Father, and become Christians, by putting on Christ in baptism, so that Jesus' blood makes us perfect in the sight of God, even though we are sinners, we are at peace with God - pure in his sight/ acceptable to God, as long as we are striving to do what is right in the sight of the Lord, and thereby living a life in service to Him (which is to the Father first through Christ Jesus, then our family, then our church family, then all people), even unto death.

I really liked this movie it was so powerful and strengthening. I liked the fact that the director was able to combine drama, comedy, love and inspiration without making the movie boring or a clich of other movies. It was very unique in it's ideas and I loved the plot of the movie. I don't think the intent of the director was to project men in a bad light and just show a man that was almost about to cheat on his wife. I think the director was truing to show how in marriage you have to fight for your marriage and not be so easy to give up on it. I think the woman and both the man thought their marriage was over and they were allowing the enemy to steal their happiness and love from each other. But when the woman stood up and said I'm going to change my ways and stop nagging him and start praying for our marriage it opened up the spirit realm and it begin to change her marriage for the better. For the man in the movie I think he was hurt and he was projecting his hurt into his job and overworking himself to deal with his failed marriage. He almost thought that the answer was in another woman. But when he saw that his wife still cared for him it opened up his hurt wounds that he had been trying to conceal and he wanted to fight for his marriage too again. But God was showing us that someone has to step up and take a stand, whether it is man or woman. So for the people that gave the movie a 1 I will say to give the movie another chance and look at it with an open heart. I was skeptical of watching the movie myself because I thought it was going to be another depressing movie about a man cheating on his wife and going to leave her. But basically the older woman in the movie was sent as a messenger telling the younger woman not to repeat the mistakes that she made in her marriage. She didn't fight for her marriage with strength and persistence. She fought with words and hate and it was a losing battle. And you know what the whole moral of the movie was: when a soldier goes into battle it is crucial that they do not leave their weapons at home because the fight is not always physical it is spiritual and mental. And the reason so many marriages and relationships is not experiencing victory is because they are fighting with their words and not with the strength of their hearts.

This movie blessed me. Marriage is (to me) one of the hardest personal jobs to perform and yes, I said job. I mean so in the sense that it takes a lot of sacrifice, work and perseverance for it to work and this movie presents the true key to a successful marriage, prayer and faith. I can relate to the main character's struggles and victory. If not for God my marriage itself would be over, however I had to learn how to fall in love with God wholly and completely, totally surrendering my life to Him and trusting Him to work all areas of my life out. And He is, He has, and He will continue to do so because I trust Him totally and completely. So yes, I recommend this movie to every and anyone who is struggling in life. I've just watched War Room and can understand why it gets 5-star ratings from folks who feel excited about certain things.
For example, there's a "happy ending".  An elderly woman is portrayed as having a long-time relationship with God and has learned and matured in her relationship with Him.  This older woman actually teaches a younger woman, which hints at someone taking Titus 2:4-5 to heart. The movie appears to portray Christianity in a positive light which is perhaps a relief from the contempt heaped on by the entertainment industry at large. There are some family value and some relationships are mended.  There's also a message that there's spiritual warfare involved in human relationships; something I believe mainstream Christianity can agree with.  If you look hard enough there's a notion that spiritual battles are not against flesh and blood (Eph 6:12).
So some things to "feel good" about.
I'd say I'm far from the most discerning person but some problems with the story troubled me.
As portrayed in the story, the prayers of the elderly and younger woman seem to lack awareness of Jude 1:9-10. This mistake happens but as theatrical examples it was disappointing.
Secondly, the younger woman is initially portrayed as an "average person who believes in God," which to me implies she is not a bonafide spiritually alive Christian.  Sure her prayer life is said to be lukewarm but the greater issue would be whether she has a relationship with Christ at all.  Later in the film she seems to be portrayed as a presumably genuine Christian who is taking her prayer life seriously but what happened in-between?
Thirdly, I might want emotionally to simply enjoy this film standalone as a quasi pro-Christian story. But I took a step back away from it to consider the gender roles portrayed and to consider this story as one among the other Kendrick films, and when I do that I can't help but sense an issue coming up.  I recall other films portraying the husband as "THE" messed-up person who needs to be fixed. For example: that man is not a strong enough leader. That man needs to step up. That man is too worldly. The heroine is the older woman. This film portrays one of the younger women's friends, a well-known speaker at Christian conferences in real life, delivering the line that "submission is learning to duck so God can hit your husband."  I didn't replay to write the line down, but believe this is a very, very close paraphrase. At best it might have been a portrayal of an error on the part of one of the women but at worst it seems to play to the Self-Righteous Women of God version of Girl Power.  Later on the film presents an Ideal Moment Scene in which the husband is physically on his knees before his wife, crying, and asking his wife for forgiveness. Too many Kendrick movies end up this way.
Real life in our culture has positively no shortage of women who behave in ways that not only fall short, but actually fall short in ways that are morally and relationally really, really depraved.  I should like to ask the Kendrick brothers to write a film in which a wife is presented as the central figure who is erring and walking in sins that need to be forsaken. I feel saddened concerning what might be the prospects for such a film to be produced.

The Kendrick Brothers once again released another movie. This time,they released that will encourage and inspire viewers to use the power of prayer as a weapon in life's trials and difficulties in War Room.

War Room tells the story of a couple - Tony and Elizabeth - who have great jobs as a pharmaceutical sales rep and housing sales agent respectively,a big expensive house,a nice and beautiful smart daughter in Danielle. The family have experienced a lot of success. But apparently,the relationship of the couple have been strained as Tony and Elizabeth has been arguing and fighting constantly. Added to that,Tony has become distant to his wife and daughter by being too focused on maintaining his status of being the top salesman of his company and has had temptations of cheating on her wife by pursuing a relationship with Veronica Drake.

One day,Elizabeth met an old widow Clara,who happens to be religious and who wouldn't hesitate to preach to her about Jesus. As Elizabeth and Clara got to know each other better,the latter thought her about the power of prayer. Clara encouraged her to bring her troubles to God through prayer and to read the Bible. Added to that,she also asked her to have an empty room where she could spend time praying to the Lord and to make this as her so-called "war room". Things become better for Elizabeth as Tony became a better husband as well as father to Danielle. Aside from that,they were able to overcome a lot of trials and life challenges they have experienced with the help of prayer. In the end,the family achieved love and happiness with the help of God.

Many especially unbelievers have trashed the movie calling it unrealistic as it criticized how Tony and Elizabeth basically overcame the domestic difficulties they have easily by prayer. Others claimed that everything was resolved easily. For unbelievers particularly atheists,prayer is basically defined as a person "talking to the wind".Apparently,they do not buy the message that the film about the power of prayer as an effective weapon. But miracles do happen. Millions of Christians have attested to it and died for Christ throughout history.

I know that this is a Christian film. I do agree to the some top movie critics that this is so-called "preach to the choir" movie. Christians will definitely enjoy it. It was evident as it managed to earn a lot at the box office and possibly the highest grossing film produced by the Kendrick Brothers. But what makes this film wonderful is that it isn't too preachy and it does not overwhelm people with Bible verses and religious beliefs. In fact,bible verses were not part of the dialogues as they are simply posted at the walls of Elizabeth's "war room" and at the end credits. While religious beliefs never became dominant in the film. Also,we have engaging characters in Elizabeth and Tony,which were portrayed well by first-time actress Priscilla Shirer and T.C. Stallings respectively. Added to that,Clara was played well by Karen Abercrombie. We get to see them in funny moments. One that I like most is Priscilla's performance when Elizabeth as condemning the devil at her house. Finally,the film was great in encouraging people to pray and use it as a powerful weapon when facing difficult situations in life. With this said,I would say that this is a must-see Christian movie.

War Room is very Oprah Winfrey, but not very Biblical. The sweet old black lady who talks more to the Devil than she talks to God, tells the "troubled wife" something that perpetuates three lies. "You have to forgive others before you can ask God to forgive you." First, God forgave all sin two-thousand years ago when Jesus Christ shed His blood on Calvary. "IT IS FINISHED!" means that God is no longer in the business of forgiving sin. God IS in the business of bringing the un-believer to belief - which is the act of repentance. Second, the notion that we must "forgive-to-be-forgiven" comes from improperly interpreting the Sermon on the Mount. That was an OLD TESTAMENT even. All JEWS - no CHRISTIANS. JEWS who were convinced that if they could be as good as the Pharisees then they would be righteous enough for heaven. So Jesus gave them several "higher standards" of conduct - SINCE THEY WANTED TO LIVE AND EARN RIGHTEOUSNESS BY THE LAW. Third, nowhere in the New testament does a person ask God for forgiveness of sins, nor does a writer of the various books and letters require the asking, begging, confessing, etc. that our pastors teach us we must do to get our sins forgiven.
Either God forgave all sin when Jesus shed His blood on the cross, or God did not forgive all sin when Jesus shed His blood on the cross. To teach that your pre-salvation sins are forgiven when you invite Jesus into your heart (that's not in the Bible) and that your post-salvation sins are forgiven at your convenience when you do one of several works (confess, ask, negotiate, forgive-to-be-forgiven, etc.) is telling God that Jesus did not finish His work - that you will finish it for Him. And then you will wonder why you are being told, "Depart from Me - I never knew you." If you are believing in the Jesus of WAR ROOM, you are believing in a different Jesus. And if you believe that you have to forgive others before you cn ask God to forgive your sins, then you are denying the finished work of Jesus Christ.

I don't know about you, but I love seeing families put back together again, I love hearing stories of how Doctor's had given up on people causing them to turn to the Great Physician and having their sick bodies healed. If anyone is going through a storm in their life, and they know they need somebody bigger than themselves to turn it around, please watch this movie!
Thank you for your time.
-Daniel
